1. Introduction
SECP is a simple, educational chat protocol that demonstrates multiple network
communication patterns:
• UDP broadcast for discovery and public chat
• UDP multicast for scalable open-room messaging
• UDP unicast for direct invitations and closed-room messaging
• TCP for reliable, guaranteed-delivery rooms
• Optional encrypted TCP for private guaranteed rooms
SECP prioritizes clarity and ease of implementation over performance and security.
2. Terminology
The key words MUST, MUST NOT, SHOULD, SHOULD NOT, and MAY are to be interpreted as
described in RFC 2119.
• User: A participant identified by a username.
• Room: A named chat space.
• Room Owner: The user who created the room.
• Open Room: A room anyone may join or leave freely.
• Closed Room: A room requiring invitation from the owner.
• Guaranteed Room: A room using TCP for reliable delivery.
• Private Guaranteed Room: A guaranteed room restricted to invited users; may be
encrypted.
• Presence Message: A periodic announcement sent by each client.
3. Protocol Overview
SECP uses:
• UDP (port 50000) for presence announcements, room advertisements, invitations, and
for chat in UDP-based rooms.
• TCP (port 50001) for chat in guaranteed-delivery rooms.
Clients discover users/rooms via periodic UDP broadcast messages. Room type determines
how messages are sent.
4. Transport and Ports
4.1 Ports
Purpose Protocol Port
UDP communication UDP 50000
TCP server for guaranteed rooms TCP 50001
All UDP messages MUST be sent to port 50000.
All TCP servers MUST listen on port 50001.
4.2 Broadcast
UDP broadcast MUST be sent to the local subnet broadcast address (e.g., 192.168.1.255) or the
limited broadcast address 255.255.255.255, depending on platform constraints.
4.3 Multicast (Chosen Address)
SECP uses IPv4 multicast for open user-created rooms.
• Multicast group: 239.0.0.1
• UDP port: 50000
• TTL: MUST be 1
Educational simplification: All open multicast rooms MAY share the same multicast group.
Clients MUST filter based on the ROOM field.
5. Message Format
All protocol messages are UTF-8 encoded text with fields separated by the pipe character (|):
TYPE|ROOM|USERNAME|PAYLOAD
• TYPE: Message type identifier (see below).
• ROOM: Room name, or - if not applicable.
• USERNAME: Sender username.
• PAYLOAD: Message-specific content (may be - if not applicable).
5.1 Message Types
• PRESENCE — announces a user
• ROOM_ANNOUNCE — advertises an open room
• INVITE — invites user(s) to a closed/guaranteed/private room
• CHAT — a chat message sent to a room
6. Presence Announcements
When an application starts, it MUST broadcast presence every 10 seconds as long as it is
running.
Format
PRESENCE|-|username|ip-address
Transport
• UDP broadcast to port 50000
• Interval: 10 seconds
7. Chat Rooms
Rooms are identified by a case-sensitive room name. Room names MUST NOT contain | and
SHOULD be short (<= 32 characters).
Each chat message sent to a room MUST include both USERNAME and the message text (via
the CHAT message format).
8. Room Types
SECP defines multiple room types to demonstrate different network patterns:
• Open Rooms allow anyone to join freely and demonstrate UDP broadcast/multicast.
• Closed Rooms require invitations and demonstrate UDP unicast communication.
• Guaranteed Rooms use TCP and demonstrate reliable client/server chat.
• Private Guaranteed Rooms restrict access and MAY use encryption over TCP.
8.1 Global Open Room: "USN Chat" (UDP Broadcast)
The global open room is a shared public chat space on the local network. It demonstrates UDP
broadcast and provides no delivery guarantees.
• Room name: USN Chat
• Transport: UDP broadcast
Chat messages:
CHAT|USN Chat|username|message
8.2 User-Created Open Rooms (UDP Multicast)
User-created open rooms allow unrestricted participation while reducing broadcast traffic. They
demonstrate UDP multicast; clients join the multicast group to receive messages.
• Room announcement: UDP broadcast every 10 seconds
• Chat transport: UDP multicast (239.0.0.1:50000)
Room announcement format:
ROOM_ANNOUNCE|room-name|owner|OPEN
Chat message format:
CHAT|room-name|username|message
8.3 Closed Rooms (UDP Unicast)
Closed rooms restrict access through invitations from the owner. They demonstrate targeted
UDP unicast communication without delivery guarantees.
• Invitation: UDP unicast
• Chat transport: UDP unicast (between participants)
Invitation format:
INVITE|room-name|owner|CLOSED
Chat messages:
CHAT|room-name|username|message
8.4 Guaranteed Rooms (TCP, Invitation via UDP Broadcast)
Guaranteed rooms provide reliable delivery using TCP. The owner acts as TCP server;
participants connect as TCP clients.
• Invitation: UDP broadcast every 10 seconds
• Chat transport: TCP (owner-ip:50001)
Invitation format:
INVITE|room-name|owner|TCP
8.5 Private Guaranteed Rooms (TCP, Invitation via UDP Unicast)
Private guaranteed rooms restrict access to invited users. They demonstrate reliable point-to-
point communication and MAY be encrypted.
• Invitation: UDP unicast
• Chat transport: TCP (owner-ip:50001)
Invitation format:
INVITE|room-name|owner|TCP_PRIVATE
9. Room Discovery and Invitations
9.1 Open Room Discovery
• USN Chat is implicit and always available.
• User-created open rooms MUST be advertised via UDP broadcast every 10 seconds
while the room exists using ROOM_ANNOUNCE.
9.2 Invitations
Invitations MUST include:
• room owner username (in USERNAME)
• room name (in ROOM)
• room type (in PAYLOAD)
For invited rooms, the owner MUST send INVITE using UDP unicast.
Note: Since the base message format does not include an explicit destination username,
implementations SHOULD include the invited username inside PAYLOAD for unicast invitations,
e.g.:
INVITE|room-name|owner|CLOSED;to=invitedUser
(Implementations MAY choose an equivalent simple convention.)
10. Message Delivery Rules
Room Type Transport Reliability
USN Chat UDP broadcast Unreliable
Open user-created UDP multicast Unreliable
Closed UDP unicast Unreliable
Guaranteed TCP Reliable
Private guaranteed TCP Reliable
11. TCP Communication
11.1 Connection
• Room owner MUST listen on TCP port 50001.
• Participants connect to the owner’s IP address on port 50001.
11.2 Framing (Line-Delimited)
Messages sent over TCP and UDP MUST:
• be UTF-8
• be terminated by newline \n
11.3 TCP Chat Message Format
All chat messages over TCP MUST use the same CHAT format:
CHAT|room-name|username|message
There is no difference in message structure between UDP and TCP; only the transport differs.
12. Optional Encryption
Private guaranteed rooms MAY use encrypted data transfer.
Recommendation: TLS SHOULD be used if encryption is implemented.
If encryption is enabled, the TCP connection for that room MUST be established using TLS.
Message format remains the same (line-delimited UTF-8), but transported inside the encrypted
channel.
13. Error Handling
• Unknown TYPE values SHOULD be ignored.
• Malformed messages (wrong number of fields, missing fields, invalid UTF-8) SHOULD be
discarded.
• No error responses are required.
14. Security Considerations
SECP provides no authentication, authorization, integrity, or replay protection by default. Users
can spoof usernames and messages. UDP traffic may be lost or duplicated. This protocol is not
suitable for production use.
